  "prompt": "So, is it illegal to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It is a serious financial crime that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal of money laundering is to make the funds appear legitimate.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and significant prison sentences, sometimes up to 20 years or more, depending on the severity of the offense.\n\nSimilarly, in the United Kingdom, the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002** criminalizes money laundering, and offenders can face up to 14 years in prison, unlimited fines, or both. Other countries have comparable laws and severe penalties for money laundering.\n\nInternational organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** also work to combat money laundering globally by setting standards and promoting effective legal and regulatory frameworks. Overall, money laundering is a universally recognized crime with serious legal consequences.",
